To determine if an integer \( n \) is a power of three without using loops or recursion, you can use bitwise operations. Specifically, you can use the property that a number \( n \) is a power of three if and only if \( n \) is a perfect cube. A number \( n \) is a perfect cube if there exists an integer \( k \) such that \( n = k^3 \).

Here is a Java solution that uses this property:

```java
public class PowerOfThree {

    public static boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        // Calculate the cube root of n
        int cubeRoot = Integer.bitLShift((int) n, 3);

        // Check if the cube root is an integer
        if (cubeRoot!== Integer.intBits(cubeRoot)) {
            return false;
        }

        // Check if n is a perfect cube
        return n == cubeRoot * cubeRoot;
    }

